##"I'm fighting death for a patient" | dialogue with ICU Doctor Li Shengqing

Wechat, renwumag1980

Feature Introduction, the best Chinese character report

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At the moment, the most thrilling battlefield in Wuhan has been transferred to the intensive care unit. At 5 p.m. on Feb. 22, a large screen in the doctor's office monitors the condition of each bed in the intensive care unit of the Tongji Medical College. Patients in beds 11 and 19 had just died, and nurses were pulling tubes out of them one by one.
Several doctors stood in front of the screen, looking at everything in the room, frustrated. One of the patients, who were not on the critical list, was doing well during the morning assessment and took a turn for the worse in the afternoon. "everyone is doing everything they can to stay alive, " said one doctor, "but the disease is changing so fast that it doesn't give you a chance to prepare. "In the evening came the news that the patient in bed 18 had also died. In one day, three people died in the ICU.
Tongji Hospital Guanggu district has a total of 17 medical teams, the management of the hospital 828 critical care beds. The medical team of Mount Hua Hospital took over the intensive-care unit, receiving critically ill patients transferred from other wards. Accidents Happen, and in their cases, some patients die in the toilet, others die in the middle of a meal, and there's no time to save them.
Since February 11, every day at 3:00 p.m. in the lecture hall, Death Panels have been held, with representatives from 17 teams discussing difficult and fatal cases. One doctor at the meeting described the sudden death of his patient during a meal, expressing pain and confusion: "How could it happen so fast? How could it happen so fast? "? It feels like a straw just broke the camel's back. "
Li Shengqing, head of ICU in Tongji Guanggu district, is the chief of Respiratory Department of Huashan Hospital, who has experienced SARS, but the severity of the new outbreak is still beyond her experience. She summed up her work as "taking patients from death. ". In the ICU bed, you can see some patients have been on several machines, "so small body surrounded by a group of machines, many patients are like this, completely surrounded by machines... I think it is really tragic, if you worked in our ICU for a long time, you'd know it was brutal. Brutal. "
After the deaths of several of the patients, Li Shengqing has been travelling in advance of the customs, pre-intervention, pre-treatment. At present, the death rate of Tongji Hospital in Guanggu district is lower than that of most hospitals.

The following is a conversation between people reporter and Li Shengqing.

By Luo Ting

Editor, sugar maple

People: You've been in charge of the ICU for more than ten days. How did you feel at the beginning?

Li Shengqing: When I decided to come, I thought, I was doing dangerous breathing disease, Wuhan Front so many comrades fell down, the patient died, I can not sit still, anxious, so came. I've been through SARS. I know what to do. But when I got there, what broke me was what we called the critical care ICU, which was just a bed and a bedside table, but with the heaviest patients. So, by all means, let's bag the ekg, the inhaler. By now, the basic configuration of the suction machine enough, there are nearly 30 sets of creative suction machine.

In fact, all our patients here are pre-invasive, because in the general ward, he gives them both oxygen and non-invasive, and if that doesn't work out, he has to be intubated to get here. We have 30 beds, 27 patients intubated at the most.

People: You repeatedly referred to the "pass forward" , is under what circumstances to reach this conclusion?

Li Shengqing: The reason why I mention it is because of the blood lesson. I think it was four days ago, I went in for rounds, I went through all the patients, I adjusted the vacuum, the patients were all stable, I was quite happy, I don't think any patients will die today, I was glad to take off my protective clothing and go out, before I got to the doctor's office, they told me that the 15 beds were in a straight line and the 4 beds were in a straight line. It was amazing. How do you think I felt.

The two patients weren't hooked up to a breathing machine, they were non-invasive and had good pulse oxygen, 92% , 93% , because the guidelines said, if we keep his pulse-ox at 88% to 93% , I don't think he needs to be upgraded? And here we are. So I made up my mind to move forward.

People: In a straight line, does that mean it's beyond saving?

Li Shengqing: Yes, that's the ending. The guidelines say 88% to 93% , I go above 93% , and if you don't, I'm GonNa have to intubate you. 93% , 94% I think it's dangerous. In the later stages of the disease, the disease develops and deteriorates at an accelerated rate. I have suffered so many losses, now repeatedly stressed that the threshold forward, and then forward is not wrong, but if missed the opportunity to rescue this patient, it is really irreversible.

People: When you say "suffered many losses, " does that mean it happened more than once?

Li Shengqing: There is another patient, I found that he was in the oxygen condition, 95% has been unable to maintain, only 93% . He was immediately put on a non-invasive (breathing) , on the found that the improvement is still not obvious, or 93% , I told his doctor-in-charge, immediately to intubate the breathing machine, called the intubation team. But the intubation team hesitated, saying the patient was adamant. I said leave him alone. I'll call his family. Just get me dressed and get in there.

They put their clothes on, I get permission from the family. By the time anesthesiologist was intubated, his pulse ox was only 85% noninvasive, half an hour, that fast. After the emergency intubation, it's now 100% . So why do I keep bringing up the threshold, if we wait until he's 85% , 86% , and we get dressed before we go in, you don't have to go in, the patient's over, it really is that fast.

Li Shengqing (first from left) discusses the patient's condition with medical staff

People: Pulse ox 85% . What does that mean?

Li Shengqing: It means severe respiratory failure, which means someone is going to die, and it also means you have to intubate him in three to five minutes.

People: Why so fast, as you say, Split Second.

Li Shengqing: It is determined by the characteristics of this disease, which is progressing very fast and impairs the function of multiple organs, especially the heart and kidney. Many patients are due to explosive Myocarditis, caused by heart failure, sudden death, the incidence is very high. They were breathing fine, died of heart failure, cardiac arrest.

I feel like I'm at war with death every day. He grabbed me, too. Let's see who gets the best. Let's see who's quick. I blinked, and he took a bunch of patients, and I moved forward, and you had to hold on, or else you wouldn't have time to react. It's not like a normal ward. The patient is quite good. Wait a little longer. When he fails, you say, "Oh, I'm going to intubate. I've been wearing a protective suit for half an hour. I don't need to come in. I don't need to wear it. ".

People: At the last death seminar, a doctor said that most of the new patients in the ICU did not die in bed, but in the toilet, and died suddenly while eating. It is said that other patients died within minutes of their non-invasive transformation. Why is this happening?

Li Shengqing: In fact, the patient is already in the state of oxygen depletion, there is no oxygen reserves. As long as you leave the breathing support, you can't maintain the oxygen supply to your vital organs, and you die quickly. Sometimes the disease or light enemy, such patients as soon as possible on breathing, intubation. Sometimes you're a minute late, and you never get another chance.

(Note: The discussion among the doctors at the meeting showed that not every death was known to the doctors. Because it is difficult to move critically ill patients for CT and echocardiograms while still giving them oxygen, some doctors say it can sometimes be difficult to detect subtle changes in the patient's body. And because many patients have underlying diseases, whether they end up dying from other underlying diseases also needs to be discussed. Li's approach is to record data on the patient every five to 10 minutes, including heart rate, blood pressure, breathing, oxygen saturation and so on, to see if the patient dies of heart failure, or failure, or other problems.)

"PEOPLE" : If this is the case, the threshold forward, what measures can be specific?

Li Shengqing: If it endangers the kidney, then we can use renal replacement therapy, which is fine. To endanger the heart, I now think of the method of early intervention is first IABP (intra-aortic balloon pump, is one of the mechanical auxiliary circulation method, can increase coronary artery blood supply, improve myocardial function) . I brought this intervention forward, to give it a cardiac assist. And as it turns out, we did reduce mortality by bringing it forward.

If the lung is in danger, intubate first, we have a lot of ICU in, oxygen saturation 70% , 80% , this belongs to the rescue, definitely intubation, do not hesitate. There are still some questions, 93% , 94% , you think it's OK, do you want in or not? Ask The patient again, the patient says I'm not GonNa do it, and you hesitate. You hesitate for half an hour, he dies.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Yin Xiyuan, a critically ill patient, was dying

People: You are Director of smoking department, also experienced SARS, have seen such scenes before?

Li Shengqing: No, I have never seen such a big scene even though I was in crisis. There may be three or four of them in my ward, the heaviest of them all, but they're not that dense, and they're all too tired to touch the ground. I was in the west Beijing hospital for SARS, and the patients I came in contact with were light. For the first time in my life, 30 beds, 27 in intubation, one on ECMO, and five or six on renal replacement therapy. We use every tool at our disposal to keep the patient alive, and that's exactly what we're doing.

People: We saw today in the ward, a patient on three machines, Ecmo, renal replacement therapy and suction machine.

Li Shengqing: Yes, so small body was surrounded by a group of machines, many patients are like this, completely surrounded by machines, how tragic. You can see how hard we've worked to keep him here. I just think it's really bad, and if you work in our ICU for a long time, you know it's really bad, it's really bad.

And if you think about it, every patient dies with no family, strangers like us, strangers who can't even see their faces, and their eyes are behind their goggles. Isn't it tragic that when he dies, all his family gets is a box of ashes. He deserves to be loved and respected by everyone in the world. But because of this epidemic, many new pneumonia patients in Wuhan leave without dignity, without love feeling.

People: And from the monitoring, the workload of each medical staff in the ward is very heavy, and it never stops.

Li Shengqing: Because of the rapid change of the condition, I ask the doctor to check the patients and tour the ward at any time according to the need of the condition. In addition each intubation patients with a nurse, the nurse every 30 minutes to go on a tour, non-stop tour, at any time to find changes in the condition, at any time to adjust treatment program. It really was like a war, so I told them we were friends for life and death.

We've got a 1-to-6 ratio, six nurses to a bed. The average ICU is 1 to 3, Sometimes 1 to 2. With so many critical patients in such a short period of time, and you're working a limited number of hours, usually four to six hours, and with that amount of time, I would never put us all at risk.

Image courtesy of intensive-care unit

People: You would also think that this is already the best group of people in China who know how to keep people, but some deaths are inevitable.

Li Shengqing: Yes, why does the patient die when he goes to the toilet? Why does he die when he eats? This shows that we lack a prediction and an estimate of the severity of the disease. After the pass is moved forward, you can prevent him from eating to death, going to the toilet to death, is to reduce the mortality rate. My goal right now is to lower the mortality rate, and I'm going to use all the tools at my disposal, the life support tools at my disposal, the life support tools at my disposal, the life support tools at my disposal, the life support tools at my disposal, the life support tools at my disposal, the life support tools at my disposal, the life support tools at my disposal, the life support tools at my disposal, the life support tools at my disposal, the life support tools at my disposal, the life support tools at my disposal, and then I.

People: in the ICU, there are a small number of patients who are awake and articulate. What do they talk about most?

Li Shengqing: actually did not say anything, I found that patients have a characteristic, after entering the ICU, it seems that they are prepared for the worst, this ICU is the last stop. It's a question mark. There's only five of us out there.

People: Do they have any chance of getting better after the INTUBATION, how much?

Li Shengqing: We are trying, now is to maintain, not allowed to die, first give you drag to live here, so we still have a chance. We had a relatively minor patient who was extubated. Tomorrow I pick up a patient and get him to do SBT, as if it's lowering the parameters of the machine, lowering the support for him, I see how he's doing on his own, I'll get him off the phone if I can, but I still have a tube on him, so I can plug it in whenever I want, and if he's fine when he goes offline, then I can pull it out safely.

Now they've got enough breathing support, and then there's intensive care ICU management, and I want multidisciplinary collaboration to get US intubated patients out of the ICU as much as possible, that's what we're going to do next.
